# check for Null Values and deal with them

    num_nan = data[col].isna().sum()
    pct_nan = (num_nan / len(data)) * 100
    print(f"Column {col} has {num_nan} NaN values ({pct_nan:.2f}%).")

if 'Age' in data.columns:
    missing_before = data['Age'].isnull().sum()
    
    average_age = data['Age'].mean()
    data['Age'].fillna(average_age, inplace=True)

    missing_after = data['Age'].isnull().sum()
    rows_updated = missing_before - missing_after
    
    print(f"Rows with NULL (NaN) 'Age' replaced with average ({average_age:.2f}): {rows_updated}")
else:
    print("The 'Age' column does not exist in the DataFrame.")

# Kernel Distribution Estimation

goldMedalsBasketball = merged[(merged.Medal == 'Gold')&(merged.Sport == 'Basketball')]
goldMedalsSwimming = merged[(merged.Medal == 'Gold')&(merged.Sport == 'Swimming')]

sns.kdeplot(data=goldMedalsBasketball["Height"],shade=True,label="Basketball")
sns.kdeplot(data=goldMedalsSwimming["Height"],shade=True,label="Swimming")

plt.legend()
plt.show()
# The KDE depicts the probability density function of the continuous numeric variables, considered analogous to a histogram
# KDE Plot for height variable for gold medal-winning athletes in basketball and swimming sports.

# We can clearly see in the KDE plots that the probability of winning gold is higher for a basketball athlete if he/she is tall, whereas height is a relatively small factor when it comes to winning gold in swimming

# Area Plots: similar to Line Plots
womenGold = merged[(merged.Sex == 'F') & (merged.Medal == 'Gold')& (merged.Season == 'Summer')]
menGold = merged[(merged.Sex == 'M') & (merged.Medal == 'Gold')& (merged.Season == 'Summer')]
womencount=womenGold.groupby(womenGold.Year).count()
mencount=menGold.groupby(menGold.Year).count()
x=pd.DataFrame(womencount.ID)
x=x.rename(columns={"ID": "Women"})
y=pd.DataFrame(mencount.ID)
y=y.rename(columns={"ID": "Men"})
NumberOfGold=x.join(y)


NumberOfGold.plot.area(stacked=False,figsize=(18, 8))
plt.title('Medals won by woman in comparison with men per edition of the Games')

# As a consequence of more female athletes since 1980, we can also see a spike in the number of gold medals won by women
# This is an important observation, as based on the data before 1980, we can wrongfully conclude that a male athlete has a higher chance of winning gold as compared to a female athlete
# Hence, we can say that there is a bias known as prejudice bias present in this dataset

# A lag plot is a special kind of scatter plot in which the X-axis and Y-axis both represent the same data points, but there is a difference in index or time units. 
# The difference between these time units is called lag.

#shuffle dataset
merged=merged.sample(frac=1)
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6), dpi=80)
pd.plotting.lag_plot(merged.Weight,lag=1)

# Here the data seems to be completely random, and there appears to be no pattern present. Hence the data also fulfills the randomness assumption.

# We now also know that there is a chance that we can drop either the weight or height feature without losing much information about the data. 
# Also, it is clear that the data is biased, and if we use this data to train any model, it may produce a model biased against female athletes.
